{"parentUuid":"8616fd7d-ec0e-42ea-90a3-2d11d5032202","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a62a4b9fae3247ab0","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccq1PqexTBG1jsRBdg7r6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both large-feature triggers are met, so all three artifacts are written. I ran the step-8 self-audit against the rubric and it passes; summary below.\n\n## Self-audit result: passed\n\nVerified before handing over:\n- **All applicable layers have a section** — Backend, Data/migrations, Auth, Logging, API edge, DAST; Infrastructure and Frontend are explicitly marked no-change/N-A (backend API, no design source) rather than silently omitted.\n- **What/why/how inline with dismissed alternatives** — the tenant model, PUT-as-upsert, the `FOR UPDATE` strict-enforcement mechanism (rejecting the single-statement CTE, `SERIALIZABLE`, and advisory locks), and the `app_code` error-facade extension each carry rationale and tradeoffs.\n- **STRIDE model** — 12 threats, each with severity + a concrete mechanism (library/SQL/config + file) + ASVS ID; includes the enabling conditions the rubric demands (lock ordering → no deadlock; RLS non-owner-role condition; fail-secure rollback; unlimited-path takes no lock). Mermaid DFD + copy-paste prompt both present.\n- **Validation contracts** — every boundary input tabled with type + bound + anchored allowlist + sink + file.\n- **Files affected / Test strategy / Stack notes / Open questions** — all concrete; `pyramid` declared with rationale; three open questions carry proposed defaults.\n- **acceptance.md** — `criteria_total: 22`, `delegated_criteria: [AC22]` (ASVS reconciliation → security); each AC traces to a named test; AC20 is a measurable perf budget (p95 < 50 ms on `POST /v1/events` with quotas active); AC16 states the precise reversibility kind; a `data_protection_waiver` records the non-sensitive classification.\n- **Input-surface controls** — the new `PUT /v1/quotas` input carries both a validation AC (AC5) and a Tier-2 principal-keyed rate-limit AC (AC15); `POST /v1/events` enumerated as pre-existing.\n- **tasks.md** emitted (crosses both triggers); the union of `ACs advanced` covers AC1–AC21, with AC22 intentionally delegated.\n\n## Key design calls the checkpoint should weigh\n\n1. **Strict enforcement via a `SELECT … FOR UPDATE OF q` lock on the quota row**, atomic with the rollup increment inside the existing per-request transaction — a rejected event's row is rolled back, so usage can never exceed `L` and replays of accepted events never re-check the quota. The alternatives (guarded-CTE upsert, `SERIALIZABLE`, advisory locks) are named and dismissed in the plan.\n2. **Tenant model (Open Question 3):** quotas bind to a single `api_key_id`, so a quota-using tenant provisions **one admin-scoped key that both ingests and administers** (admin = ingest superset). This is the only model under which enforcement binds with the current single-key-per-tenant schema; multi-key-per-tenant is out of scope per the brief.\n3. **RLS enabling condition (Open Question 2):** `quotas` mirrors the existing `ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` (not `FORCE`), effective only if the app DB role is a non-owner — flagged for confirmation, with the explicit `api_key_id` filter as the primary control regardless.\n4. **PUT latency budget (Open Question 1):** proposed p95 < 100 ms as a documented target, not a load-tested AC (admin-only, low-traffic single upsert).\n\nArtifacts written:\n- `C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\plan.md`\n- `C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\acceptance.md`\n- `C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\tasks.md`\n\nPlan is ready for human review. I have not implemented anything — a human reviews the plan and threat model next."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_crea